		<div id="about" class="sixteen columns add-bottom">
			<h2>About</h2>
			<p>Homesick is my graduation project at the Interactive/Media/Design department at <a target="_blank" href="http://www.kabk.nl/">The Royal Academy of Art</a>, the Hague. It started out as <em>Call Me They</em> – a response to my exploration of gender as a continuum rather than a binary. Over time though, my feelings of being homesick for India over powered the rest. After a five year gap I finally had a chance to visit India again last year. Once there I discovered that my childhood home had been sold, soon to be demolished and replaced by an apartment building. My family there had moved from the neighbourhood I spent 18 years in to the outskirts of Delhi. And the Delhi I knew had been replaced by something entirely new. This loss meant that my homesickness had not been cured despite visiting the country twice in six months. I felt more Indian than I had ever done before, yet it seemed as though a large part of me was missing. I tried to deal with these emotions. Bring them out in my work, but I couldn't figure out how to. The thoughts remained with me very strongly.</p> 

			<p>I started to immerse myself in Indian movies, music and news. And tried to bring out this 'Indian-ness' in every aspect of life. Even my thesis on gender had a strong Indian influence to it. Therefore, I believe over time this seeped into my subconscious and had a very dramatic impact on the trajectory of this project. Unbeknownst to me this installation had become a lot about my need to find a cure for my homesickness.</p> 

			<p><em>Thanks to Avrïl Jacobson, Micca Teo, Luka Kueter and Maya Yenna. </em></p>
		</div>
